+# ACP Pilot 57 ‚Äî Safety Hardening
+
+## Metadata
+
+| Field | Value |
+|---|---|
+| **Pilot identifier** | `ACP-PILOT-57` |
+| **Date** | `2026-07-20` |
+| **Reviewed issue / PR** | `lydia/home-repo#64` |
+| **ACP version used** | `0.1.0-draft` |
+| **Reviewer** | OpenCode Agent (michael) |
+| **Review result** | `PASS_WITH_FINDINGS` |
+
+## Summary
+
+Pilot 57 reviewed the Safety Hardening milestone in `lydia/home-repo` (PR #64),
+which introduced workspace confinement, path traversal detection, command
+validation, and an execution gate. The ACP specification at `0.1.0-draft` was
+effectively empty (no normative content), so the review was conducted against the
+intent of ACP rather than its letter. All observations below emerged from this
+first-ever application of the protocol to a real PR.
+
+## Observations
+
+### Implementation
+
+| # | Observation | Severity | Affects ACP |
+|---|---|---|---|
+| 1 | `path_sanitizer.sh` hardcodes `WORKSPACE_DIR="$HOME/workspace"` ‚Äî not configurable via environment or parameter | `medium` | ‚Äî |
+| 2 | `is_within_workspace` uses `realpath -m` (mathematical-only, no symlink resolution) ‚Äî a symlink inside the workspace pointing outside bypasses confinement | `high` | ‚Äî |
+| 3 | `execution_gate.sh` duplicates path-traversal and system-path checks that already exist in `path_sanitizer.sh` ‚Äî DRY violation | `medium` | ‚Äî |
+| 4 | `safe_execute.sh` hardcodes Gitea URL `http://192.168.2.30:3000` and token path `~/.creds/gitea.token` ‚Äî not portable | `medium` | ‚Äî |
+| 5 | `safe_execute.sh` uses `source` with `$HOME/home-repo/` ‚Äî assumes a fixed checkout location | `medium` | ‚Äî |
+| 6 | No input size limits before regex matching in `detect_path_traversal` ‚Äî potential ReDoS risk on untrusted input | `low` | ‚Äî |
+
+### Prompt
+
+| # | Observation | Severity | Affects ACP |
+|---|---|---|---|
+| 1 | The review prompt asked the reviewer to apply ACP, but with an empty spec the reviewer had to infer ACP intent from the repository README alone | `medium` | `¬ß1` |
+
+### Reviewer
+
+| # | Observation | Severity | Affects ACP |
+|---|---|---|---|
+| 1 | No formal ACP conformance checklist existed at the time of review ‚Äî each finding was identified ad-hoc | `high` | `¬ß3` |
+
+### ACP
+
+| # | Observation | Severity | Affects ACP |
+|---|---|---|---|
+| 1 | ACP `0.1.0-draft` contained no normative content ‚Äî `SPEC/` was a `.gitkeep` directory. Every pilot before the spec is written produces meta-findings, not protocol findings | `high` | all |
+| 2 | No findings workflow existed before this pilot. Observations from PR #64 were not persisted anywhere accessible to future reviewers | `high` | `¬ß4` |
+| 3 | No mechanism exists to trace a finding from a pilot back to a specific ACP revision | `high` | `¬ß4` |
+
+## Recommendation
+
+**Candidate for future ACP revision?** `Yes`
+
+**Rationale:** Pilot 57 was conducted without a normative spec, which is the
+single largest finding. The protocol must define at minimum:
+- The structure of a review package (what the reviewer evaluates)
+- The verdict format (what constitutes pass/fail)
+- The findings taxonomy (so future pilots classify consistently)
+
+Until these three elements are written, every pilot will produce observations
+that are unrepeatable and incomparable across reviews. Pilot 57's findings
+directly inform which sections of ACP need to be written first.
+
+## References
+
+- ACP specification: `SPEC/.gitkeep` (normative content not yet written)
+- Related decisions: `DECISIONS/` (none yet)
+- Reviewed PR: `lydia/home-repo#64` ‚Äî Milestone 6: Safety Hardening
+- Findings workflow: `FINDINGS/README.md`
+- Template for future pilots: `FINDINGS/TEMPLATE.md`
